No lint errors, so the issue is likely behavioral. Looking at the code, I can see the problem now:

In the `setSpinnerListener()` method on line 118, the touch listener always returns `true`, which consumes the touch event and prevents the spinner from opening normally. The intention seems to be to show a custom `DeckSelectionDialog` instead of the normal spinner dropdown, but the current implementation prevents any interaction with the spinner.

The issue is in this part:
```kotlin
fun setSpinnerListener() {
    spinner.setOnTouchListener { _: View?, motionEvent: MotionEvent ->
        if (motionEvent.action == MotionEvent.ACTION_UP) {
            displayDeckSelectionDialog(collection)
        }
        true  // <-- This prevents normal spinner behavior
    }
    setSpinnerVisibility(View.VISIBLE)
}
```

By always returning `true`, we're telling the system that we've completely handled the touch event, which prevents the spinner from responding to touches. We should only return `true` when we actually want to consume the event.

Let me check if there are any usages of this class to better understand the expected behavior.

